post_text:
Congratulations and many thanks to Stephenville’s own Vice Admiral Luke McCollum, who retires as Chief of Navy Reserve tomorrow, Friday, August 7th.

The ceremony will be live streamed at 8:30AM Texas Time. The public is invited for the Change of Command and Retirement ceremony, which is taking place at the Admiral Leutze Park, Washington Navy Yard, DC at this link:

https://allhands.navy.mil/Live-Stream



McCollum became the 14th Chief of Navy Reserve in September 2016. As commander, Navy Reserve Force, he has led approximately 60,000 Reserve Component personnel who support the Navy, Marine Corps and joint force. More information about his long and distinguished Navy career is available at https://www.navy.mil/Leadership/Biographies/BioDisplay/Article/2236142/vice-admiral-luke-mccollum



McCollum is a 1979 graduate of Stephenville High School, and was honored in 2016 as a Stephenville High School Distinguished Alumnus by the Stephenville Optimist Club and the Stephenville Education Foundation.

post_text:
While keeping the health and safety of our students, staff, and families in mind, SISD initiated the establishment of an agreement with Cook Children's Health Care System to provide the following services to our administration and nursing departments.

Consultation and consulting services regarding the SISD re-opening protocols, procedures, and duties

Physical on-site auditing of campus activities and processes

Consultation with administration regarding closing and re-opening processes should cases be identified within the schools

Updated information from the medical community regarding any changes to best practices or protocols

Attendance by a Cook Children’s representative at School Health Advisory Committee meetings

Special education student health reviews

Consultation on general health related questions

We look forward to seeing our students soon!

post_text:
The health and safety of our students, staff and families are of the utmost importance to us. This unprecedented time is unnerving and we are all attempting to make our way through it in the safest way possible.

All students will now begin school on Wednesday, August 19th, which was the original start date. This decision will allow our teachers and administrators more time to train, prepare, and plan for the new safety protocols.

Campus start and end times are as follows:
Central Elementary: 7:45 a.m. - 3:20 p.m.
Chamberlin Elementary: 7:55 a.m. - 3:30 p.m.
Hook Elementary: 7:50 a.m. - 3:25 p.m.
Gilbert Intermediate: 7:50 a.m. - 3:35 p.m.
Henderson Junior High: 8:00 a.m. - 3:40 p.m.
Stephenville High School: 7:55 a.m. - 3:48 p.m.

post_text: As a district, we are saddened by the recent events and conflicts occurring in the nation, and we do not condone nor support racism or any form of discrimination. In the past week we have witnessed the best and worst of our school community. We are committed to, and we believe it is our responsibility to sustain an environment that fosters a caring and compassionate culture. In today’s virtual world, we will continue to do everything in our power to reinforce our district and community values.

All four of the major United States carriers — AT&T, Sprint, T-Mobile, and Verizon — have signed on to the FCC’s Keep Americans Connected Pledge. Under this agreement, carriers have agreed to take the following action for at least the next 60 days:

Not terminate service to any residential or small business customers because of their inability to pay their bills due to the disruptions caused by the coronavirus pandemic;

Waive any late fees that any residential or small business customers incur because of their economic circumstances related to the coronavirus pandemic; and

Open its Wi-Fi hotspots to any American who needs them.

SISD students can connect their school devices to mobile hotspots. This will help with the delivery of instruction through the extended closure.

Stephenville ISD will be providing 2 service opportunities regarding breakfast and lunch availability free of charge for all of our students beginning March 16-18, 2020.

1. Curbside pickup for both lunch and breakfast will be offered from 7:30-8:30 am at Henderson Junior High in the bus lane (back of school).

2. For students that participate in morning and/or afternoon transportation services, buses will run routes beginning at 8 am and should arrive at bus stops approximately two hours later than normal stop times. Breakfast and lunch will be delivered to the student pickup/drop off location. We encourage students’ (and parent/guardian(s)) to be available for receipt of these items.
*Detailed route information will be provided on the SISD transportation website.
*If you are a PM rider only, you may contact the Transportation Department (254-968-3759) for an approximate time if desired.

HEART OF GOLD:
OCTOBER 18, 2019

The Heart of Gold recipient this year is BABY NOAH. Heart of Gold T-shirt order forms were placed in all High School ENGLISH Teacher's boxes Friday afternoon (Oct 4). Teachers, please make sure to get these forms handed out to every English student on Monday, Oct 7 because the DEADLINE to turn in these orders is Friday, Oct 11. Students turn all forms back into their English teacher and the t-shirts will be delivered to the English teacher to hand out. T-shirts will be delivered between Oct 15-17. Please encourage your students to wear their Heart of Gold T-shirt to school on Friday, Oct 18 and let them know we will also wear them at the Varsity Football game here on Oct 18 where there will be a special presentation on behalf of Baby Noah at the beginning of this game .

ALL OTHER ORDERS MUSH GO TO ATHLETIC OFFICE.

post_text: Last week, the Yellow Jacket Jazz Ensemble participated in the Region 7 Jazz Auditions in Graham and came away with 17 students earning spots in one of two bands. Each band consists of 5 saxes, 5 trumpets, 5 trombones, 1 piano, 1 guitar, 1 bass, and 2 drum set. We placed almost half of the available spots with SHS students! Nine students were selected to record an audition for the all-state jazz band. The full region placement is listed below and all-state results should be released in November. These students will participate in the All-Region Jazz Clinic and Concert in February.

post_text: #initiative Officer Payne and Mr. Nation are amazing!
shared_text:
The Flash Today - Erath County
May 1, 2019 at 4:28 PM ·

BEFORE & AFTER SNAPS OF A WONDERFUL COMMUNITY PROJECT –– Stephenville School Resource Officer Benny Payne saw a need for picnic benches at Henderson Jr. High for the Life Skills students to be able to have a place to sit and work outside on nice days. The kids thrive when allowed to work outside but didn't have a place to sit that accommodated their needs. Officer Payne was able to get two benches destined for the dump from the city of Stephenville, McCoy's Building Company donated supplies and Bruce Nation, the Construction Technology and Architecture at Stephenville High School, and his students refurbished the tables. Staffers at HJH said they believe this project "is a continued testament of how giving our town is when a need is presented."
Special thanks to Flash reader EVA GUINN for the pictures and information.
THANK YOU, OFFICER PAYNE & MR. NATION & EVERYONE ELSE INVOLVED IN THIS GREAT PROJECT!!!!

Stephenville Empire Tribune
April 25, 2019 at 7:47 PM ·

The Stephenville Yellow Jackets posted an important District 7-4A baseball victory over Mineral Wells Thursday afternoon, 3-1. The win improves the fourth-place Jackets to 3-4 in district, with their final regular-season district game set for Friday at home (7 p.m.) against Glen Rose, which is in second place at 5-2. Godley, currently third at 4-3, has to face district-leading Brownwood Friday. Wins Friday by both Stephenville and Brownwood would force a one-game district playoff between SHS and Godley for third place to avoid having to play No. 1-ranked Argyle (27-1-1) in the opening round of the playoffs. Thursday's game originally was scheduled to be played Tuesday night in Mineral Wells, but was rained out and moved to Glen Rose where there is an artificial turf to avoid any potential mud problems.

post_text:
Good afternoon. In addition to being out of school for Good Friday and a bad weather day on Monday, Stephenville ISD will not be having school on Thursday!

The Honeybee Soccer team may have an opportunity to play for the State Championship on Thursday at 2:30 pm in Georgetown. As a district of innovation, SISD has the flexibility to adjust the district schedule and provide our families and friends with a full day off to support the team on Thursday.

Also, we would like to invite the community to meet by the courthouse on the square tomorrow to give the team a huge Stephenville sendoff! Please be on the square tomorrow by 10:20 so you don’t miss the excitement! The bus will travel east on Washington and turn right onto Graham street.

School will resume on Tuesday, April 23rd. Report cards will be sent home at that time.

Thank you for supporting our students!

post_text:
As a part of the The UIL Young Filmmakers Festival, SHS student Sierra Hastings film "Angels and Demons" was selected as one of the six state finalists in Digital Animation. Her film will be shown at Paramount Theater in Austin on March 5th. At that time Sierra will be awarded her official medal and specific placing (1st - 6th).

While working on her film Hastings’ used the inspiration of the angel and demon as your conscience. She wanted to convey the point “people never go away, and you can let them drown each other out and lose your sense of reality.” Hastings goes on to say, “In the end what the video is trying to convey is you. You are telling yourself these things, and if you focus on your demon, you need to fall back and listen to the other shoulder.”

Hastings stated the message of the film to be “Always look for the light positive. It will be okay in the end.”

Congratulations to this talented student! To view the film, click the link below.

http://bit.ly/2tLVsCx

He is married to Mandi and has three boys Cooper (10), Kipton (8) and Cohen (4).

December 9, 2018 at 8:34 PM ·

4TH PLACE FISHING FINISH! The Stephenville High School fishing duo of Caden Cowan and Hunter Mayo snagged a 4th place finish at the Texas High School Bass Association Tournament held in Lewisville Saturday. Their finish helped move Stephenville into an overall 3rd place finish out of the 32 schools and 193 teams taking part. The fourth-place finishers were awarded $250 scholarships and gift cards.

post_text:
SHS Bass Club fished in the Texas High School Bass Association West division tournament on Possum Kingdom Lake on Saturday, November 3rd. 14 teams competed for SHS. Stephenville finished 2nd place out of 33 schools. A total of 221 teams fished in the tournament.

Clayton and Trevor Easter finished in 1st place with 5 fish weighing in at 16.25lbs and winning biggest bass at 8.32lbs. Both won a $1000 scholarship.

Reece Elston and Cason Love finished in 9th place with 5 fish weighing 10.95lbs.
text:
SHS Bass Club fished in the Texas High School Bass Association West division tournament on Possum Kingdom Lake on Saturday, November 3rd. 14 teams competed for SHS. Stephenville finished 2nd place out of 33 schools. A total of 221 teams fished in the tournament.

Clayton and Trevor Easter finished in 1st place with 5 fish weighing in at 16.25lbs and winning biggest bass at 8.32lbs. Both won a $1000 scholarship.

Reece Elston and Cason Love finished in 9th place with 5 fish weighing 10.95lbs.
